limitations.description: Vocabulary is limited only to text which has been seen on online forums, where language can change a lot over time.
“Toxic” is defined as “a rude, disrespectful, or unreasonable comment that is likely to make you leave a discussion.”
Because of privacy considerations, the model does not take into account user history when making judgments about toxicity.
Synthetic test data covers only a small set of very specific comments. While these are designed to be representative of common use cases and concerns, it is not comprehensive.

ethicalConsiderations.description: This model should not replace actual content moderation, but only be an assistive tool for moderation.
This model should be updated frequently and retrained on new vocabulary seen on various online forums. These datapoints can be collected from human content moderation.

datasets.name: Proprietary Perspective API
datasets.description: This includes comments from a online forums such as Wikipedia and New York Times, with crowdsourced labels of whether the comment is “toxic”

datasets.name: Synthetic Examples
datasets.description:
A synthetic test set generated using a template-based approach, where identity terms are swapped into a variety of template sentences.

Synthetic data is valuable here because
real data often has disproportionate amounts of toxicity directed at specific groups. Synthetic data ensures that we evaluate on data that represents both toxic and non-toxic statements referencing a variety of groups.

performanceOverview: We measure performance based on Pinned AUC, which measures threshold-agnostic separability of toxic and non-toxic comments for each group, within the context of a background distribution of other groups.
primaryGoal: Intended to be used for a wide range of use cases such as supporting human moderation and providing feedback to comment authors.

groupImpacts.impact: There are terms this model is intended to see in text that focus specifically on harmful slurs against people of various sexual orientations, gender identities, and race.
